tmux-custom (drpedapati fork)
=============================

A custom fork of tmux that tracks upstream (https://github.com/tmux/tmux)
and layers in opinionated defaults for a modern terminal workflow:

  - F-key bindings with no prefix required (phone-friendly)
  - Catppuccin theme with automatic macOS dark/light switching
  - Tabs show current directory name instead of hostname
  - `tmux` with no args attaches to existing session or creates one
  - Built-in WakaTime/Wakapi time tracking (fires on pane focus)
  - F12 session/directory chooser via sesh + fzf
  - F1 shows full key binding reference
  - Session save/restore via tmux-resurrect (survives restarts)
  - Auto-save every 15 min via tmux-continuum

Install
-------

  $ brew install --HEAD drpedapati/tools/tmux-custom

This installs tmux-custom plus all required tools:
wakatime-cli, sesh, fzf, zoxide.

Then start tmux:

  $ tmux

Key Bindings (no prefix required)
-----------------------------------

  F1            Key binding reference (this list, inside tmux)
  F2            New window
  F3 / F4       Previous / next window
  F5            Split left/right
  F6            Detach
  F7            Copy mode
  F8            Rename window
  F9            Split top/bottom
  F10           Other pane
  F11           Kill pane
  F12           Session/directory chooser (sesh + fzf)

  Shift+F3/F4   Previous / next pane
  Ctrl+F3/F4    Swap pane backward / forward
  Ctrl+F6       Kill pane
  Ctrl+F8       Rename session
  Shift+F8      Cycle layout
  Shift+F11     Zoom pane
  Alt+F11       Break pane to new window

  M-Left/Right  Previous / next window
  M-Up/Down     Previous / next session
  Shift+Arrows  Select pane by direction

Session Backup (resurrect + continuum)
-----------------------------------

Sessions are saved automatically every 15 minutes and restored on startup.

  prefix + Ctrl-s   Save session now
  prefix + Ctrl-r   Restore last saved session

Requires the one-time plugin clone above. Saves to ~/.local/share/tmux/resurrect/
by default. Survives kill-server, reboots, and brew upgrades.

Time Tracking (Wakapi)
-----------------------------------

tmux-custom fires a heartbeat every time you switch panes, tracking
time automatically by project directory. Sends to wakapi.dev — a
free, open-source WakaTime-compatible backend. Works across all your
machines with one account.

Setup:

  1. Create an account at https://wakapi.dev and copy your API key.

  2. Create ~/.wakatime.cfg:

       [settings]
       api_key = YOUR_KEY_HERE
       api_url = https://wakapi.dev/api

  2. Start tmux — tracking begins automatically.

  No ~/.wakatime.cfg or no api_key = silent no-op, zero overhead.

--------

Welcome to tmux!

tmux is a terminal multiplexer: it enables a number of terminals to be created,
accessed, and controlled from a single screen. tmux may be detached from a
screen and continue running in the background, then later reattached.

This release runs on OpenBSD, FreeBSD, NetBSD, Linux, macOS and Solaris.

* Dependencies

tmux depends on libevent 2.x, available from:

	https://github.com/libevent/libevent/releases/latest

It also depends on ncurses, available from:

	https://invisible-mirror.net/archives/ncurses/

To build tmux, a C compiler (for example gcc or clang), make, pkg-config and a
suitable yacc (yacc or bison) are needed.

* Installation

To build and install tmux from a release tarball, use:

	$ ./configure && make
	$ sudo make install

tmux can use the utempter library to update utmp(5), if it is installed - run
configure with --enable-utempter to enable this.

To get and build the latest from version control - note that this requires
autoconf, automake and pkg-config:

	$ git clone https://github.com/drpedapati/tmux.git
	$ cd tmux
	$ sh autogen.sh
	$ ./configure && make
	$ sudo make install

* Contributing

Bug reports, feature suggestions and especially code contributions are most
welcome. Please send by email to:

	tmux-users@googlegroups.com

Or open a GitHub issue or pull request.

* Documentation

For documentation on using tmux, see the tmux.1 manpage. View it from the
source tree with:

	$ nroff -mdoc tmux.1|less

A small example configuration is in example_tmux.conf.

Other documentation is available in the wiki:

	https://github.com/tmux/tmux/wiki

Also see the tmux FAQ at:

	https://github.com/tmux/tmux/wiki/FAQ

A bash(1) completion file is at:

	https://github.com/scop/bash-completion/blob/main/completions/tmux

For debugging, run tmux with -v and -vv to generate server and client log files
in the current directory.

* Support

The tmux mailing list for general discussion and bug reports is:

	https://groups.google.com/forum/#!forum/tmux-users

Subscribe by sending an email to:

	tmux-users+subscribe@googlegroups.com

